<paragraph blockId="68.[151,1437,152,2018]" box="[198,1435,1912,1938]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis box="[198,330,1912,1937]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin meaning “wonderful,” in reference to the large size and beauty of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="68.[151,1437,152,2018]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis box="[198,301,1952,1977]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Remarks</emphasis>
. This large species is described on the basis of a pair collected 
<emphasis box="[1063,1174,1952,1977]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">in copula</emphasis>
. The female is easily identified due to its broad, quadrate head, broad mesosoma, and lack of a scutellar scale.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1436,152,258]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">The male has the apical metasomal segments clothed with dense conspicuous silver setae. Tergum II has two to four conspicuous, yellow/orange maculae. The maculae may be distinct (four), but sometimes the lateral maculae coalesce to form two hourglass-shaped maculae.</paragraph>
